ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:10` – the reverse‑print loop declares `size_t i` and tests `i >= 0`. Because `size_t` is unsigned, when `v.size()` is `0` the expression `v.size()‑1` wraps to the maximum value, so the condition is always true; the loop never terminates and on the next iteration it reads `v[i]` past the vector’s end, causing an out‑of‑bounds read that ASan reports as a container‑overflow and otherwise results in an infinite hang.  

LOCAL FIX: replace the faulty loop with a version that cannot underflow. One minimal edit is:

```diff
-    for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
-        std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
-    }
+    for (int i = static_cast<int>(v.size()) - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
+        std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
+    }
```

This uses a signed loop variable, so the termination condition correctly becomes false once `i` reaches `‑1`, eliminating the overflow and the associated OOB access.  

GLOBAL FIX: adopt a design that eliminates raw unsigned index arithmetic in reverse iteration throughout the codebase, for example by requiring all reverse loops to use `std::reverse_iterator` (or a range‑based reverse view) and by adding a clang‑tidy check that flags the pattern `for (size_t i = ...; i >= 0; ...)`; this prevents the entire class of underflow‑induced infinite loops and container‑overflows by enforcing safer traversal idioms at the API level.

